prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Sample A: Brightest objects at 0.2'' resolution.
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
Band-7 images (continuum and 13CO and C18O lines) at 0.2" resolution.
Class II sources with K-band < 10 mag (stellar masses > 0.5 to 0.8 M_solar) and Class I and Flat Spectrum objects. Two array Configurations: C36-4 + (C36-2 or C36-3) to obtain high-resolution images and also recover flux and structures at all relevant scales, from 25 AU to ~1000 AU (e.g, from the inner disk to the envelopes of Class I sources.
Continuum sensitivity = 0.3 mJy/beam Line sensitivity = 35 mJy/beam in each channel (0.4 km/s)
Main Objectives: measure disk mases, sizes, and structures in detail.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our correlator set-up delivers a 0.4 km/s spectral resolution for the J=3-2 transitions of 13CO and C18O and a total bandwidth of 6.6 GHz for continuum observations. The aggregated continuum sensitivity is 0.3 mJy per beam. The line sensitivity is 35 mJy per beam in each of the 0.4 km/s channels. The expected line widths are 2 to 5 km/s, and thus they will be well sampled by our observations.

For Sample A (Class II objects brighter than K-band = 10 mag and Class I and Flat Spectrum sources), we request an angular resolution of 0.2 arcseconds (25 AU) to study their structure: disk size, surface density profile, asymmetries, etc. The typical disk around an 0.5 M_solar star in Ophiuchus has a masss of 5 M_Jup, corresponding to ~75 mJy in band-7 (Andrews & Williams, 2007). Since our observations will have a sensitivity of 0.3 mJy, we expect to obtain a higher signal to noise ratio per beam (by a factor of ~5) than achieved by Andrews et al. (2009,2010), the largest imaging survey of Ophiuchus disks (resolution = 0.3", rms = 2-3 mJy, 17 targets brighter than 75 mJ at 850 microns). As masive disks in Ophiuchus could be as large as 4" or more on the sky (r ~ 250 AU, Andrews et al. 2009), we have set the Largest Angular Scale to 5". This will require the observations to be obtained with two array configurations: C36-4 + (C36-3 or C36+2).

We request a line sensitivity of 35 mJy per 0.4 km/s channel per beam (or ~25 mJy per km/s per beam). This translates into an observing time of ~1 minute per source and is enough to detect 0.1-0.3 M_Jup of gas per beam (3-sigma, see Figure 1). The corresponding continuum sensitivity is 0.3 mJy or 0.2 M_Earth of dust per beam at the distance of our targets.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Sample B: fainter objects at 0.5" resolution
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
Band-7 images (continuum and 13CO and C18O lines) at 0.5" resolution.
Class II sources with K-band > 10 mag (disks around lower mass stars) and Class III disks. Class III targets have weak but significant (>5 sigma) 24 micron excesses.
One array Configuration: C36-2
Continuum sensitivity = 0.3 mJy/beam
Line sensitivity = 35 mJy/beam in each channel (0.4 km/s)
Main Objectives: measure disk masses and sizes.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our correlator set-up delivers a 0.4 km/s spectral resolution for the J=3-2 transitions of 13CO and C18O and a total bandwidth of 6.6 GHz for continuum observations. The aggegated continuum sensitivity is 0.3 mJy/beam. The line widths are expected to be 2 to 3 to 5 km/s and thus the lines will be well sampled by our observations.

For Sample B (Class II objects with K-band > 10 mag), we request observations at 0.5"(62.5 AU) resolution, corresponding to the C36-2 array. These observations are meant to be partially resolved (e.g., sufficient to measure disk sizes, without compromising gas and dust sensitivity). In this configuration, the largest angular scale that we can recover is 7", much larger than the expected sizes of these fainter disks (< 1-2").

We request a line sensitivity of 35 mJy per 0.4 km/s channel per beam (or 25 mJy per km/s per beam). This translates into an observing time of ~1 min per source and is enough to detect 0.1-0.3 M_jup of gas per beam (3-sigma, see Figure 1). The corresponding continuum sensitivity is 0.3 mJy or 0.2 M_Earth of dust per beam at the distance of our targets (125 pc).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose a band-7 imaging survey to study the gas and dust of the entire population of disks (from Class I to III) identified by Spitzer in Ophiuchus, the closest of the major star-forming regions in the solar neighborhood. The correlator set-up includes the J=3-2 transitions of 13CO and C18O. We will observe each of the 289 targets at at fixed sensitivity and vary the spatial resolution (from 0.2" to 0.5") based on the known or expected mm flux. The resulting wealth of data will enable numerous individual projects and will have a long-lasting legacy value. The survey will be invaluable for both demographic studies and the identification of interesting sources for detailed followup observations. However, we have designed the survey based on the following 3 main scientific objectives: 1) Trace the evolution of the gas and dust from the Class I to Class III stage, 2) Study the dependence of disk properties on SED Class, stellar mass, and environment, and 3) Investigate the full diversity of structures present in protoplanetary disks. The underlying motivation of the program is to provide much needed observational constraints on disk evolution and planet formation theory.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
